
test_hash_hmac: User container for calculating HASH and HMAC

Load the container and see usage in logs:
$ mwtest.py -c100 run test_hash_hmac.img
$ cmtest log
CI: First message:   ALGO CORE [KEY]
CI: Next message(s): DATA or unaligned/empty for final
CI: ALGO:  sha-224|sha-256|sha-384|sha-512|sha-512_224|sha-512_256|
CI:        sha3-224|sha3-256|sha3-384|sha3-512|shake128|shake256|whirlpool
CI: CORE:  s2hc|s3hc|cshc|whc
CI: KEY:   string/binary or %.. for hex data
CI: DATA:  string/binary or %.. for hex data
CI: Waiting for SIC input on flow 0x64...

For example, to hash empty input with sha-256 and SHA3 core:
$ cmtest cmd -f100 sha-256 s3hc
$ cmtest data -f100 ""
00000000: e3 b0 c4 42 98 fc 1c 14  9a fb f4 c8 99 6f b9 24  |...B.........o.$|
00000010: 27 ae 41 e4 64 9b 93 4c  a4 95 99 1b 78 52 b8 55  |'.A.d..L....xR.U|

For example, to hmac mydata with key mykey:
$ cmtest cmd -f100 sha-256 s3hc "mykey"
$ cmtest data -f100 "mydata"
00000000: 02 bf 82 84 3f bb 96 2a  15 50 a4 f8 be b9 b4 97  |....?..*.P......|
00000010: c3 10 d3 37 5c 76 2c ed  4f 95 00 0b 12 02 d0 01  |...7\v,.O.......|

Any invalid input or invalid setup will make the container fail and exit with
error. Final and close will be called on empty or unaligned input.
When using SHAKE the HC is never closed because SHAKE yields endless output.

Unload the container:
$ mwtest.py -c100 unload
